# 2) Loop through each, load & QC‐filter
filtered_adatas = {}
for sd in sample_dirs:
    # load
    ad = sc.read_10x_mtx(f"data/{sd}", var_names='gene_symbols', cache=True)
    ad.obs['sample'] = sd
    
    # QC metrics
    ad.var['mt'] = ad.var_names.str.startswith('MT-')
    sc.pp.calculate_qc_metrics(ad, qc_vars=['mt'], inplace=True)
    
    # filters
    sc.pp.filter_cells(ad, min_genes=200)
    sc.pp.filter_cells(ad, max_genes=6000)
    ad = ad[ad.obs.pct_counts_mt < 15, :]
    sc.pp.filter_genes(ad, min_cells=3)
    
    print(f"{sd} post‐filter: {ad.n_obs} cells × {ad.n_vars} genes")
    filtered_adatas[sd] = ad

# Now `filtered_adatas` holds each cleaned AnnData, keyed by sample name.

import scanpy as sc

# 1) Sample folders and tissue map
sample_dirs = [
    "Case1-YF", "Case1-ZY",
    "Case2-YF", "Case2-ZC", "Case2-ZY",
    "Case3-YF", "Case3-ZY",
    "Case4-ZY"
]
tissue_map = {
    "Case1-YF":"Tumor",
    "Case1-ZY":"Metastasis",
    "Case2-YF":"Tumor",
    "Case2-ZC":"Normal",
    "Case2-ZY":"Metastasis",
    "Case3-YF":"Tumor",
    "Case3-ZY":"Metastasis",
    "Case4-ZY":"Metastasis"
}

# 2) Build list of filtered AnnData objects (from your previous QC step)
ad_list = [filtered_adatas[sd] for sd in sample_dirs]

# 3) Concatenate, labeling by sample (unique!)
adata = sc.concat(
    ad_list,
    label='sample',      # new obs column “sample”
    keys=sample_dirs,    # one‐to‐one with ad_list
    join='inner'
)

# 4) Map sample → tissue
adata.obs['tissue'] = adata.obs['sample'].map(tissue_map)

# 5) Normalize & log1p
sc.pp.normalize_total(adata, target_sum=1e4)
sc.pp.log1p(adata)

# 6) Save raw for true fold‐changes
adata.raw = adata.copy()

# 7) Drop mitochondrial genes
non_mito = ~adata.var_names.str.startswith('MT-')
adata = adata[:, non_mito]
adata.raw = adata

# 8) DE between Tumor vs Metastasis (uses raw, so log‐fc is non‐NaN)
sc.tl.rank_genes_groups(
    adata,
    groupby   = 'tissue',
    reference = 'Metastasis',
    method    = 'wilcoxon',
    use_raw   = True
)

# 9) Inspect top Tumor genes
df_tumor = sc.get.rank_genes_groups_df(adata, group='Tumor')
print(df_tumor[['names','logfoldchanges','pvals_adj']].head(10))

Preprocessing¶

Filtering thresholds and rationale: Cells were filtered using standard thresholds: minimum 200 genes per cell, maximum 6000 genes per cell, and less than 15% mitochondrial reads. These thresholds reduce noise by removing low-quality or dead cells (high mitochondrial percentage) and potential doublets or multiplets (unusually high gene count).

Cell/gene numbers before and after filtering: Specific cell and gene numbers are reported post-filtering for each sample separately. For instance, thresholds reduced sample complexity to cells typically ranging in the hundreds to thousands. Exact numbers were sample-specific, generally significantly reducing both cells and genes.

Literature-based strategies to set thresholds (non-visual): Thresholds can also be determined based on statistical methods such as outlier detection algorithms, modeling distributions (e.g., Gaussian mixture models for mitochondrial content), or using tools like scDblFinder for doublet prediction. Automated pipeline guidelines like those recommended by Cell Ranger can also inform non-visual threshold choices.

Feature Selection¶

Method explanation: Highly variable genes (HVGs) were selected using the Cell Ranger method (sc.pp.highly_variable_genes), based on variance-mean relationships of genes across cells.

Number of HVGs chosen: 2,000 genes were selected for downstream analysis.

Gene variability threshold: Exactly 2,000 genes were selected as HVGs, while the remainder were excluded.

PCA¶

Justification for PC choice: PCA was used for dimensionality reduction, and PCs selected were based on an elbow plot of explained variance. Typically, 10–20 PCs are sufficient, chosen at the point of diminishing returns on the variance-explained curve.

Interpretation: Chosen PCs encapsulate the biological variability necessary for effective clustering and visualization without excessive noise.

import scrublet as scr
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import os

# Your list of sample names and the dict of filtered AnnDatas
sample_dirs = [
    "Case1-YF", "Case1-ZY",
    "Case2-YF", "Case2-ZC", "Case2-ZY",
    "Case3-YF", "Case3-ZY",
    "Case4-ZY"
]

# Where we'll store the summary
records = []

# Make a figures folder if you want to save score histograms
os.makedirs('figures/scrublet', exist_ok=True)

for sd in sample_dirs:
    ad = filtered_adatas[sd]
    
    # 1) Extract the raw counts matrix (dense)
    counts = ad.X.copy()
    if not isinstance(counts, np.ndarray):
        counts = counts.toarray()
    
    # 2) Initialize Scrublet (e.g. 7.5% expected doublets)
    scrub = scr.Scrublet(
        counts,
        expected_doublet_rate=0.075
    )
    
    # 3) Run scrublet — returns scores and boolean calls
    doublet_scores, predicted_doublets = scrub.scrub_doublets(
        min_counts=2,
        min_cells=3,
        n_prin_comps=30
    )
    
    # 4) Add back into AnnData.obs
    ad.obs['doublet_score']      = doublet_scores
    ad.obs['predicted_doublet']  = predicted_doublets
    
    # 5) Summarize call rate
    rate = 100 * np.mean(predicted_doublets)
    records.append({
        "sample": sd,
        "tissue": tissue_map[sd],
        "n_cells": ad.n_obs,
        "doublet_rate_%": rate
    })
    
    # 6) (Optional) save a histogram of the scores
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    plt.figure(figsize=(4,2))
    plt.hist(doublet_scores, bins=50)
    plt.xlabel("Scrublet score")
    plt.ylabel("Cell count")
    plt.title(f"{sd}: {rate:.1f}% doublets")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(f"figures/scrublet/{sd}_scrublet_hist.png", dpi=150)
    plt.close()

# 7) Build & save the summary DataFrame
df_scrub = pd.DataFrame(records).set_index('sample')
print(df_scrub)
df_scrub.to_csv("results/scrublet_summary.csv")

import scanpy as sc
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import os

# 1) Load your merged AnnData (with Tumor, Metastasis, Normal)
adata = sc.read_h5ad('results/combined_all_samples_scaled.h5ad')

# 2) Compute diffusion map (10 diffusion components)
sc.tl.diffmap(adata, n_comps=10)

# 3) Build kNN graph on the diffusion map embedding
sc.pp.neighbors(adata, n_neighbors=15, use_rep='X_diffmap')

# 4) Choose a “root” cell index: prefer Normal tissue, else Tumor
if 'Normal' in adata.obs['tissue'].unique():
    root_ix = np.flatnonzero(adata.obs['tissue']=='Normal')[0]
else:
    root_ix = np.flatnonzero(adata.obs['tissue']=='Tumor')[0]
adata.uns['iroot'] = int(root_ix)

# 5) Run Diffusion Pseudotime (DPT) using that root
sc.tl.dpt(adata, n_dcs=10)

# 6) Save the updated AnnData (with dpt_pseudotime) for downstream
os.makedirs('results', exist_ok=True)
adata.write_h5ad('results/combined_with_dpt.h5ad')

# 7) Plot UMAP colored by pseudotime and save
os.makedirs('figures', exist_ok=True)
plt.figure(figsize=(5,4))
sc.pl.umap(
    adata,
    color='dpt_pseudotime',
    cmap='viridis',
    size=5,
    show=False
)
plt.title('Diffusion Pseudotime')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('figures/umap_dpt_pseudotime.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

Replication of Two Major Findings (1/2 Pseudotime)¶

Analysis replication: I replicated pseudotime analysis as best I could but was not able to replicate perfectly.

Interpretation: "Besides, the predicted pseudotime based on unsupervised RNA velocity analysis was similar in the three patients with paired tissues (P1–P3; Fig. 3d), indicating conserved differentiation trajectories among these patients. The pseudotime trajectory analysis based on Monocle2 defined five cell states (S1–S5) (Fig. 3c). Tissue-wise, ductal cells from the NT tissue were confined to S1, while ductal cells from PT and HM tissues were scattered among other states (S2–S5). Cell cluster-wise, MALAT1+ ductal cells (cluster 4) and MKI67+ ductal cells (cluster 5) dominate the S1 state, and showed up at the earliest stage during pseudotime in both PT and HM tissues, indicating their highly proliferative characteristics."

I was able to get the general appropriate trajectory of healthy cell -> tumor -> metastisis but not the more detailed version the paper was able to generate.

import scanpy as sc
from celltypist.models import Model # For loading the model
import celltypist
import os
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np # For NaN handling

# --- Configuration ---
adata_input_path = 'results/combined_all_samples.h5ad'
# Ensure this path is correct and the model is accessible
model_path = '/usr4/bf591/nwhite42/.celltypist/data/models/Immune_All_Low.pkl'

# Output directories and files
results_dir = 'results_celltypist_output_v4' # Using a new distinct output directory
figures_dir = 'figures_celltypist_output_v4'
output_adata_path = os.path.join(results_dir, 'combined_with_celltypist.h5ad')
cluster_to_celltype_csv_path = os.path.join(results_dir, 'cluster_to_celltype.csv')
umap_figure_path = os.path.join(figures_dir, 'umap_cluster_annotation.png')

# Clustering key in adata.obs (e.g., 'leiden', 'louvain')
# Make sure this key exists in your AnnData object
clustering_key = 'leiden'

# --- Main Script ---
def main():
    """
    Main function to run the cell type annotation workflow with NaN handling.
    """
    # 0) Create output directories if they don't exist
    os.makedirs(results_dir, exist_ok=True)
    os.makedirs(figures_dir, exist_ok=True)
    print(f"Results will be saved in: {os.path.abspath(results_dir)}")
    print(f"Figures will be saved in: {os.path.abspath(figures_dir)}")

    # 1) Start from the *full* merged AnnData
    print(f"Loading AnnData object from: '{adata_input_path}'")
    try:
        adata = sc.read_h5ad(adata_input_path)
    except FileNotFoundError:
        print(f"ERROR: Input AnnData file not found at '{adata_input_path}'. Please check the path.")
        return
    print("AnnData object loaded.")
    print(f"Initial AnnData shape: {adata.shape}")

    # Check for NaNs in the initial data (optional, for debugging)
    # if np.isnan(adata.X.data if hasattr(adata.X, "data") else adata.X).any():
    #     print("DEBUG: NaNs found in adata.X upon loading.")

    # 2) Normalize & log1p on every cell → this goes into .X
    print("Normalizing total counts and applying log1p transformation.")
    # It's good practice to ensure no all-zero cells before normalization
    # This also helps prevent all-zero rows which can become NaNs after log1p if not handled.
    sc.pp.filter_cells(adata, min_counts=1) # Remove cells with no counts
    print(f"AnnData shape after filtering cells with min_counts=1: {adata.shape}")

    sc.pp.normalize_total(adata, target_sum=1e4)
    sc.pp.log1p(adata)
    # The warning "adata.X seems to be already log-transformed" might appear here
    # if the input data was already logged. This is usually fine.

    # 2.5) CRITICAL: Check for and handle NaNs in adata.X BEFORE it's copied to adata.raw
    print("Checking for NaNs in adata.X before copying to adata.raw.")
    current_X_matrix = adata.X
    if hasattr(current_X_matrix, "has_sorted_indices"): # Check if it's a sparse matrix
        if np.isnan(current_X_matrix.data).any():
            print("WARNING: NaNs found in adata.X.data (sparse matrix). Replacing with 0.")
            # Modify .data attribute of the sparse matrix. This is often in-place.
            current_X_matrix.data = np.nan_to_num(current_X_matrix.data, nan=0.0)
            # adata.X is updated because current_X_matrix (which is adata.X) had its .data modified.
        else:
            print("No NaNs found in adata.X.data (sparse matrix).")
    else: # Dense matrix
        if np.isnan(current_X_matrix).any():
            print("WARNING: NaNs found in adata.X (dense matrix). Replacing with 0.")
            # For dense matrix, np.nan_to_num creates a new array.
            # Assign this new cleaned array back to adata.X. This is allowed.
            adata.X = np.nan_to_num(current_X_matrix, nan=0.0)
        else:
            print("No NaNs found in adata.X (dense matrix).")

    # 3) Copy that nice (and now NaN-free) normalized matrix into .raw (CellTypist will look here)
    print("Copying NaN-free normalized data from adata.X to adata.raw.")
    adata.raw = adata.copy()
    # Now, adata.raw.X (accessed by CellTypist) should be free of NaNs.

    # 4) Load your downloaded model
    print(f"Loading CellTypist model from: '{model_path}'")
    try:
        model = Model.load(model_path)
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"ERROR: Could not load the model from '{model_path}'. Error: {e}")
        print("Please ensure the model path is correct and the model file is not corrupted.")
        return
    print("CellTypist model loaded successfully.")

    # 5) Annotate with CellTypist
    print("Annotating cells with CellTypist (majority_voting=True).")
    # `celltypist.annotate` returns a Predictions object
    predictions = celltypist.annotate(
        adata,            # Your AnnData object (CellTypist will use .raw.X)
        model=model,      # The loaded CellTypist model object
        majority_voting=True
    )

    # Integrate predictions back into adata
    adata = predictions.to_adata()
    print("Annotation complete. Columns added/updated in adata.obs:")
    print(adata.obs.head())

    # 6) Identify the prediction column to use
    # With majority_voting=True, the key column is typically 'majority_class'.
    if 'majority_class' in adata.obs.columns:
        cell_type_prediction_column = 'majority_class'
    elif 'predicted_labels' in adata.obs.columns: # Fallback if 'majority_class' isn't there
        cell_type_prediction_column = 'predicted_labels'
    else:
        print("ERROR: Could not find 'majority_class' or 'predicted_labels' in adata.obs after annotation.")
        print(f"Available columns: {adata.obs.columns.tolist()}")
        return
    print(f"Using '{cell_type_prediction_column}' for cell type assignments.")

    # Ensure your defined clustering_key exists
    if clustering_key not in adata.obs.columns:
        print(f"ERROR: Clustering key '{clustering_key}' not found in adata.obs.")
        print(f"Available columns: {adata.obs.columns.tolist()}")
        print(f"Please ensure your AnnData object has undergone clustering (e.g., sc.tl.leiden) and the result is stored in adata.obs['{clustering_key}'].")
        return

    # 7) Collapse to cluster labels based on the chosen prediction column
    print(f"Collapsing CellTypist annotations to a single label per '{clustering_key}' cluster.")
    # Ensure the prediction column does not contain NaNs before groupby, which can cause issues.
    adata.obs[cell_type_prediction_column] = adata.obs[cell_type_prediction_column].fillna('Unassigned')

    cluster_to_type = (
        adata.obs
        .groupby(clustering_key)[cell_type_prediction_column]
        .agg(lambda s: s.value_counts().idxmax()) # Most frequent type in the cluster
        .to_dict()
    )
    adata.obs['cluster_annotation'] = adata.obs[clustering_key].map(cluster_to_type)
    print("Consensus 'cluster_annotation' created for original clusters.")

    # 8) Save results
    print(f"Saving cluster-to-celltype lookup table to: '{cluster_to_celltype_csv_path}'")
    pd.Series(cluster_to_type, name='cell_type_per_cluster')\
      .to_csv(cluster_to_celltype_csv_path, header=True, index_label=clustering_key)

    print(f"Saving updated AnnData object to: '{output_adata_path}'")
    adata.write_h5ad(output_adata_path)
    print("AnnData and lookup table saved successfully.")

    # 9) Quick UMAP of your new annotations
    # Ensure UMAP coordinates exist. If not, compute them.
    if 'X_umap' not in adata.obsm:
        print("UMAP coordinates not found. Computing UMAP...")
        # For UMAP, typically you'd use PCA computed on scaled, highly variable genes.
        # adata.X is currently log-normalized (full genes).
        # For a "quick UMAP", using PCA on this log-normalized data is acceptable.
        # If X_pca doesn't exist, compute it.
        if 'X_pca' not in adata.obsm:
             print("PCA not found in adata.obsm for UMAP. Performing PCA on current adata.X (log-normalized).")
             # Ensure n_comps is less than the number of features/samples
             n_comps_pca = min(50, adata.n_vars -1, adata.n_obs - 1)
             if n_comps_pca < 2 : # PCA needs at least 2 components usually
                 print(f"Warning: Not enough features/samples for PCA (n_comps_pca={n_comps_pca}). Skipping UMAP PCA step if too few components.")
             else:
                 sc.tl.pca(adata, n_comps=n_comps_pca)
        
        # Check if PCA was actually computed or if n_comps_pca was too low
        if 'X_pca' in adata.obsm:
            # n_pcs for neighbors should be less than or equal to n_comps_pca used in sc.tl.pca
            n_pcs_neighbors = min(30, adata.obsm['X_pca'].shape[1])
            sc.pp.neighbors(adata, n_pcs=n_pcs_neighbors)
            sc.tl.umap(adata)
            print("UMAP computation complete.")
        else:
            print("Skipping UMAP computation as PCA could not be run (likely due to insufficient dimensions after filtering).")


    # Plot UMAP if coordinates exist
    if 'X_umap' in adata.obsm:
        print(f"Generating UMAP plot colored by 'cluster_annotation'.")
        plt.figure(figsize=(7, 7)) # Slightly larger figure for better visibility
        sc.pl.umap(
            adata,
            color='cluster_annotation',
            legend_loc='on data',
            legend_fontsize=8,
            legend_fontoutline=2,
            show=False,
            title='UMAP by CellTypist Cluster Annotation'
        )
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.savefig(umap_figure_path, dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
        print(f"UMAP plot saved to: '{umap_figure_path}'")
    else:
        print("UMAP coordinates ('X_umap') not found in adata.obsm. Skipping UMAP plot generation.")

    print("\nScript finished successfully!")

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()

# --- 0) (Re)load or pick up your processed AnnData ---
adata = sc.read_h5ad('results/combined_all_samples_scaled.h5ad')

# --- 1) Make sure your raw slot contains the full log1p matrix ---
#    (do this after your sc.pp.log1p but before any scaling/regression)
#    If you haven't already, you can still overwrite raw now:
adata.raw = adata  

# --- 2) (Re)run your DE for Tissue, using raw for FCs ---
sc.tl.rank_genes_groups(
    adata,
    groupby   = 'tissue',
    reference = 'Metastasis',
    method    = 'wilcoxon',
    use_raw   = True
)

# --- 3) Pull out the Tumor vs Met DE table correctly ---
#      Note: sc.get.rank_genes_groups_df takes only (adata, group)
df_tumor = sc.get.rank_genes_groups_df(adata, group='Tumor')

print(df_tumor[['names','logfoldchanges','pvals_adj']].head(10))
